                <h2>TILES Squares primitives</h2>
                <p>
                    The TILES toolkit enables the definition, implementation and manipulation of data type primitives. The TILES Square primitives
                    allow to abstract low-level implementation details into simple primitives for bridging the digital and
                    the physical world. The primitives are implemented in the fimware of the TILES Square modules, and events
                    containing the identifier of the primitives will traverse the layers of the toolkit infrastructure upon
                    interacting with the modules of an application. The TILES toolkit differentiate between two types of
                    primitives:
                    <ol>
                        <li>input primitives - <i>originating from the TILES Squares</i></li>
                        <li>output primitives - <i>targeting the TILES Squares</i></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <div class="docs-img">
                    <img src="/images/primitives.png" alt="primitives" />
                    <br/>
                    <span>RapIoT toolkit example primitives</span>
                </div>

                <p>
                    Example of primitives supported by the TILES Square modules are listed in the tables below. In addition, the modules features
                    custom ports to be used for extending the hardware modules with primitives of your own design. To extend
                    the TILES Square primitives, see the <a href="{{extProcessUrl}}">Toolkit Extension Process</a>.
                    For a complete overview of all the currently supported interaction primitives, see the list of
                    <a href="/#/primitives">primitives</a> registered in the TILES Cloud web portal.
                </p>

                <table class="table table-striped docs-process-table">
                    <tr>
                        <td style="max-width:0;white-space:nowrap;"><b><i>INPUT PRIMITIVES:</i></b></td><td></td><td></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Primitive</th><th>Degrees of freedom</th><th>Example mapping</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Touch/Tap</td>
                        <td>Single, double</td>
                        <td>Send a command, log a quantity</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
